Using metacell to define cell-cycle dependent and independent transcriptional heterogeneity

Zohar Meir

2020-01-27

In this note we examplify the application of metacell package to identify gene co-varition in HCT116 colorectal cancer cell-line, which is indepent of the cell-cycle phases.

Cell-cycle associated expression is perhaps the most common feature to dominate transcriptional heterogeneity in scRNA databases covering proliferative cell populations. Whereas underlying mechanism and components of cell-cylce are largely conserved, its transcrtiptional signature varies greatly between different biological systems, mainly due to different replication time-scales and different fractions of proliferating cells.

One common routine of exploring transctiptional heterogeinity in single cell RNA-seq data is finding gene correlation in normalized expression matrices. The main issue with crude normalization of such datasets are that raw UMI counts are sparse, and scaling them by any model which is predicting background trends introduces strong biases. The cycling of a cell is inherently linked to its mRNA content, and therefore is highly susecptible for various biases during normaliztion of raw UMI counts.

In this vignette we wished to avoid normalization of gene counts and then computing of their correlation scores, and used the Metacell analytic platform (Baran et al., Genomee bio. 2019) to develop an estimation to the degree of correlation between any gene pair, given their cell cycle trend alone.

To achieve this, we can summarize our strategy into two main steps: 1. Construct a balanced cell-to-cell KNN similarity graph, based on expression of cell cycle genes only, that will serve as the cleanest estimate for similarity of cells based on their cell cycle phase per se.

  1. Generate a shuffled UMI vector for each cell, by randomly sampling each gene’s expresion from one of its K neareast cells, defined by the clean cell-cycle model. Gene-to-gene correlations between such shuffled vectors is expected to preserve cell cycle related gene modules, but to completely, or almost completely eliminate correlations between genes that are co-expressed or co-repressed in a cell cycle independent fashion.

But little steps for little feet, let’s start by loading the UMIs:

We can now begin working on our cell-cycle model. A good starting point will be to fish out genes that have significant correlation with at least one strong cell-cycle “anchors” (i.e., MKI67, PTTG, GINS2, ACTB),and optionally, NOT correlated significantly to any gene that is a-priori assumed to be unrelated to cell-cycle (ANXA1). in order to do so, we will create a .txt table with genes that are correlated to our anchors:

mcell_mat_rpt_cor_anchors(mat_id="mat_wt", 
        gene_anchors = c("MKI67", "PTTG1","GINS2","ACTB"), 
        cor_thresh = 0.1, 
        gene_anti = c("ANXA1"), 
        tab_fn = "HCT116_cc/cors_anchors_hct116_cc.txt", 
        sz_cor_thresh=0.7)

# cor_thresh is an important parameter, that set the mininmal correlation that a gene needs to have to at least one of the anchors, in order to be included in the list.
# sz_cor_thresh is an optional parameter, setting the maximal allowed correlation of a gene to total cell UMI counts.

For crude analysis, let’s take all genes that had a siginficant correlation withat least one of our anchors (so their names appear in the .txt table we have just saved), and create a geneSet that will help us to create the cell-cycle model:

# read table
anchors_gene_cor = read.table("HCT116_cc/cors_anchors_hct116_cc.txt", sep="\t", h=T, stringsAsFactors=F)

# get gene names and the specific anchor they are associated with
cc_genes = apply(anchors_gene_cor[,setdiff(colnames(anchors_gene_cor),c("szcor","max","negmax"))], 1, which.max)

# create a geneSet object 
cc_hct116 = tgGeneSets(cc_genes, "HCT116, Cell Cycle Associated")
scdb_add_gset("hct116_cellCycle", cc_hct116)

# create an expression matrix for cell-cycle geneSet only
mcell_mat_ignore_genes(new_mat_id = "mat_wt_cellCycle", mat_id = "mat_wt", 
                                ig_genes = names(scdb_gset("hct116_cellCycle")@gene_set),
                                reverse=T)

Optionally, we can be real Feinschmekers and narrow the genes-list we have created, by looking for additional structure within it. specifically, we can use metacell plot gene modules we find within it, and manually keep only those modules that contain known cell-cylce factors and display significant covariance:

# create 24 gene clusters of geneSet
mcell_gset_split_by_dsmat(gset_id = "hct116_cellCycle",

# after examining the plots, decide which gene modules to keep (in this case, if you followed the exact lines so far: gene modules 6, 9, 11, 13, 15, 17 and 21)
mcell_gset_remove_clusts(gset_id = "hct116_cellCycle",

                                reverse=T)

Reagrdless of whether we decided to use all cell-cycle associated geneSet (“hct116_cellCycle”, which will be used in this example) or a purified subset of it (“hct116_cellCycle_narrow”), we can now create a balanced KNN similarity graph between cells, based on expression coming from these genes only:


# create gene stats for our expression matrix:
mcell_add_gene_stat(mat_id = 'mat_wt_cellCycle', gstat_id = 'wt_cellCycle_geneStats')
#> [1] TRUE

# create a list of markers in our expression table (only filtering out very lowly expressed genes or genes that have minimal variance):
mcell_gset_filter_varmean(gset_id="wt_cellCycle_markers", gstat_id="wt_cellCycle_geneStats", T_vm=0.03, force_new=T)
mcell_gset_filter_cov(gset_id = "wt_cellCycle_markers", gstat_id="wt_cellCycle_geneStats", T_tot=20, T_top3=1)


#use marker genes and our expresion table to build a cell-cell similarity graph object:
mcell_add_cgraph_from_mat_bknn(mat_id="mat_wt_cellCycle", 
                               gset_id = "wt_cellCycle_markers", 
                               graph_id="HCT116_wt_cellCycle_graph",
                               K=100,
                               dsamp=T)
#> will downsample the matrix, N= 750 (and yes - this should have been chached
#> willl build balanced knn graph on 3285 cells and 295 genes, this can be a bit heavy for >20,000 cells
#> sim graph is missing 24 nodes, out of 3285

# K: a parameter that defines the initial attempt of the system to assign neighbors for each cell and ultimately can affect the size distribution of derived metacells.
# dsamp: a boolean parameter which indicates whether we want to downsample the expression matrix or not.

The last step added to the database a new cell-cell graph object named HCT116_wt_cellCycle_graph, which describe the similarity of between all cells in our dataset, based only on the expression of genes in “wt_cellCycle_markers” geneSet.

However, before continue to the randomization step, it is a good practice to perform some sanity checkpoint here - and try to validate that our model is indeed describing cell-cycle.

There are many different ways to approach this, but since we are using the metacell platform, it just make sense to create metacells based on our cell graph, and test whether we can position metacells along a continuum of transcriptional cell-cycle dynamics (only the fraction of cycling ones, which can vary between biological samples). In addition, we should expect that different distributions of total mRNA content per cell to be one hallmark of our cell-cycle based metacells (but not neccassaarily, especially if sequencing of libraries is not at saturation or near it):

# add explanations here
mcell_coclust_from_graph_resamp(
                coc_id="HCT116_wt_cellCycle_coCluster100", 
                graph_id="HCT116_wt_cellCycle_graph",
                min_mc_size=50, 
                p_resamp=0.75, n_resamp=100)

#> 1%...34%...100%

                mat_id= "mat_wt_cellCycle",
                mc_id= "metaCells_wt_cellCycle",

For more functions and details on plotting metacells, checkout Metacell github: https://github.com/tanaylab/metacell

Some examples for plots to test cell cycle model:

If you think that your model looks legit - well done, the longer step of the process is now behind us.

Provided with a good estimation for how cells are related to one another based on cell-cycle trends alone, we can now ask which genes are co-variating independently of it.

Specifically, we can take the original expression matrix and shuffle it, where the expression vector of each cell will be randomly sampled from the K cells that are most adjacent to it based on our cell-cycle graph:

gene_cors_cellCycle = mcell_cgraph_norm_gcor(cgraph_id = "HCT116_wt_cellCycle_graph",
                            mat_id = "mat_wt",
                            K=20,
                            min_gtot=100)

#min_gtot: a minimal threshold for total expression per gene in the downsampled matrix.

the list gene_cors_cellCycle will now holds two equally sized gene-gene correlation matrices - g_cor and r_cor, which will contain the correlation scores between and after the shuffling, respectively.

  • If the coexpression of two genes is related to cell-cycle, than we could expect that some degree of covariance between them will survive the shuffling.
  • However, if coexpression patterns are unrelated to cell-cycle, they expected to be completely eliminated after the shuffle, (statstically, if K is large enough).

We can have a supervised-look in the two matrices and see whether a specific gene-gene interaction that is intersting for us was eliminated or not.

Several plotting strategies may help us decide which gene-gene interaction is related to cell-cycle and which doesn’t in an unsupervised way:

  1. plot the maximal correlation score of each gene before and after the shuffling
#set diagonals of matrices to zero:
diag(gene_cors_cellCycle$gcor) = 0
diag(gene_cors_cellCycle$r_gcor) = 0

#plot
png("HCT116_cc/figs/wt_shuffled_max.png",width=280,height=280)
par(mar=c(5,5,1,1))
plot(
apply(gene_cors_cellCycle$gcor,1,max),
apply(gene_cors_cellCycle$r_gcor,1,max),
cex=.4, cex.lab=1.5,cex.axis=1.5,
xlab = "original max cor.",
ylab = "shuffled max cor.",
pch=19,
col="#00000030")
grid()
dev.off()
#> png 
#>   2

an example for how such plot can be interperted:

It is apparent that some genes were able to maintain at least one significant correlation, and are therefore display dynamics that are, at least in part, associated with cell-cycle.

still, it doesn’t mean that all their transcriptional covariation are fully dependent on the cell-cyle.

in order to have a more careful look at the cel-cycle based shuffle on gene correlations, we can plot a matrix (for selected genes in this example), comparing the original correlation value in its top triangle, and the shuffled correlation scores in the lower triangle:

an example for how it can look like:

lower triangle: shuffled gene-gene correlation, higher triangle: original gene-gene correlation

In principal, as cell-cycle is after all an evolutionary conserved process, we can try and use the same genes to implement our shuffling strategy in similar biological samples (not promising anything though).

In the following example, we have used the same list of cell-cycle associated genes we obtained from parental HCT116 cells (the geneSet hct116_cellCycle), in order to create a cell-cyle model and implement the shuffling strategy on DKO HCT116 cells, harboring two know-out mutation in DNA-methyltransferases (DNMT1 and DNMT3B):

if(!dir.exists("HCT116_cc/10x_HCT116_DKO/")) dir.create("HCT116_cc/10x_HCT116_DKO/")
